documentation.text:
The OpenZeppelin implementation  implements the basic ERC721 spec and ERC721Enumerable.
The token for this contract is a 32-bit NFT name that is converted to a uint256. There is no IPFS
support. Therefore the optional ERC721Metadata interface is *not* implemented. See https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-721.
The contract supports various fees and limits through the use of a single
uint256 variable options that only the contract creator/owner can set.

documentation.text:
Set one token sale price. A price is only set if 
msg.sender is the token owner; otherwise [e30] is thrown.
If there is a defined transactionFee, it must be included in msg.value.
Only the low order 32 bits of the PriceAndIssue price are set. The others are preserved
from the time of minting.
Emits a SetPrice event.
@param tokenId  ID of token that will have price set
@param price    32 bit price in gwei for each token. A 0 means not for sale.

documentation.text:
This hook is called from the OpenZeppelin ERC721 public transfer methods. It ensures
that payments occur before any transfers occur, no matter who calls the contract.
Note that this is also called from the internal _mint and _burn methods, in which case none of
the payments mechanisms apply. In the case of _mint tokenOwner (aka "from") is address 0 and
we skip all checks. _burn is not supported.

transferAllowed method is called successfully. In this case the sender only pays the 
transactionFee and all other payments are bypassed.
The token owner must be specified to retrieve the price, and if the price
is <=0, it means the token is either not for sale, or not owned by the owner.
The amount paid is specified msg.value. Except as noted above, this may be greater than 
(but not less than) the token price. For auctions this means the open price is the token price, 
and then the final price can be greater.
Payments are made in this order:
- When payment mechanisms are bypassed, a transaction fee is paid to the contract owner
- Otherwise netProceeds of (msg.value-purchaseFee) is calculated
- Then if there is a royalty it is paid on netProceeds
- Then if there are partners, they are paid on netProceeds-royalty
- Then the tokenOwner is paid on netProceeds-royalty-partnerPayout
- Finally the purchaseFee is paid to the contract owner by the token owner
If everything in here succeeds, the price for the token is set to 0. This means
the token is not for sale until the new owner sets a price.
 @param tokenOwner    Owner of the token from whom the token is transferred
 @param to            Address purchasing the token
 @param tokenId  uint256 token ID

Allow any account (msg.sender) to purchase the specified token. This calls the internal
_safeTransfer method to ensure _beforeTokenTransfer is called. _transfer only checks
that the tokenOwner owns the token. It does not care about eth balance or the caller of this method.
_safeTransfer is called to ensure a target contract implements ERC721.
setApprovals has no bearing on this function.

Allow a token owner or approved operator to transfer a token, but only if

Without payable payment attempts get error -32000 in Metamask.

documentation.text:
The token owner creates a partner offering on a token by sending an issue
to this method. The issue must specify a number of shares offered,
share price, and total share percentage > 0.
The actual per-share percentage is calculated by dividing the passed total
share percent by number of shares, and recording that in the stored issue
in the SHARE_PERCENT bits.
Once a token has an issue, it can never have another. This is ensure by checking 
for a non-0 offering state, non-0 meaning there has been an issue.
Closing the Offering
The offering is open until:
- This function is called with _issue set to OFFERING_STATE_CLOSED
- All shares are purchased

Distribute a portion of msg.value (token sale price) to each partner, as
defined by the issue and the Partner array. This ends the Partner participation
with the token.
Reverts with message pr50 if the payment to a shareholder fails. Reverts with pr51 
if the msg.sender balance is insufficient to make a payment.
A successful payout results in:
- Each shareholder mapping for a current partner address is set to 0
- The issue being set to 0
- The partners array being deleted
- The terms array being deleted
